cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   The reason I don't automatically play FILM-X is that Opps rarely pre-empt at red vs green and that's normally the only time I'd really miss having a Penalty double.

At white vs red, however, it's worth considering using FILM-X, even if the opportunities will be few and far between.

In other circumstances I find it's difficult to get rich defending when they've pre-empted and normally you have something better on your way (eg: 3NT)

You can play FILM-X over 4-level pre-empts too: One modification there you might consider is that over 4@s, 
or over 4@h when you don't have 4-card Spades, play 4NT for takeout rather than 5@c

Any questions or comments about FILM-X or generally about defending against pre-empts?
|n#|5|at|
^*baflac: ^*n When you say red vs green ? 

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   Yes: I mean it's worth considering using FILM-X in situations where THEY are vulnerable (red) and YOU are not vulnerable (green).

That's the most likely time that you'll get a decent penalty rather than playing in a game yourselves.
|n#|5|at|
^*bP0STM0RTEM: ^*n Will playing this affect decisions in the balancing seat when the direct seat passes ?

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   No. FILM-X doesn't apply in 4th seat over the pre-empt, because you are sat UNDER the pre-empter and as such it's much LESS likely that you're in the right place to penalise them.|
