cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   Next up is a defence to Transfer Pre-empts.

This is a convention I created and licensed in the UK back in the 1980's when 3-level transfer pre-empts were quite popular.

4-level ones have always been popular and remain so (ie: Texas and South-African texas).

Although they are not quite as "in vogue" as they used to be you will still occasionally come up against transfer pre-empts at the 3-level.

As with the Dixon defence to Multi 2@d (which we'll be coming to) the possible actions are different for 2nd-in-hand (who is guaranteed another chance to bid) and 4th-in-hand (who is NOT guaranteed a second bite at the cherry).

Terminology for this section: 

^c@.   ^*b Transfer ^*n ^f Suit  is the suit Opps have actually   BID 
|n^|9|at|
^c@.   ^*b Pre-empt ^*n ^f Suit  is the suit they've actually     SHOWN

for example

If  3@c  shows a  Diamond  Pre-empt  then:
|n^|9|at|  
^c the ^*b Transfer ^*n Suit is  @c's   and   @d's  is  the ^*b Pre-empt ^*n Suit|
