cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Next up is how to defend against a Multi 2@d Opening

You may not play against many Multi 2@d if you concentrate on ACBL events, but the Multi remains very popular in the REST of the world (it's only unpopular in the USA and UK,  "thanks to"  the ACBL and EBU).

Consequently it is worth knowing how it works and how to defend against it.

Multi's come in a number of guises, the main common-denominator being that one of the options is always a weak 2 in either Major.

Sometimes that's ALL it shows but usually there is a "strong" option as well, sometimes strong balanced, but Precision Pairs often use it for a strong 4441 hand (The "complex" version of my system does, for example).

Multi uses a kind of "Oliver's Twist" in that the rationale behind the responses are that responder bids the cheapest suit he would not support at a higher level, So over 2@d  
|n^|5|at|
     2@h is "to play" if Opener has a weak 2 in @h's (but might have game interest opposite Spades.
|n^|5|at|
     2@s is "to play" if Opener has a weak 2 in @s's, but WILL have definite Game interest if Opener has a weak 2@h's.
|n^|5|at|
     2NT shows a strong hand and is forcing on Opener to show their Hand-type and Range.

Defending against Multi is a little like defending against a transfer pre-empt and, just as over my suggested defence to those, 2nd-in-hand has far more options than 4-in-hand, since they ARE guaranteed a second opportunity to bid (but bear in mind that, especially if Opener will always have a weak 2 in a Major and there is no strong option, Responder may pass with a weak hand and long diamonds).|
