cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  The scheme for Bergin when ^*b BOTH ^*n of Opps suits are known is as follows: 
|n^|5|at|
^b  @.   DOUBLE is ostensibly for PENALTIES, showing values for defence and no fit for Partner's suit.
|n^|5|at|
^b  @.   CH@2EAPEST  available cue-bid shows a LIMIT or a FORCING raise in Opener's suit   (Opener assumes the limit raise and bids accordingly. If Opener signs off and Responder has the forcing raise, they bid on).
|n^|8|at|
So if partner opens 1@h and their LHO bids 2@h showing Spades and Diamonds, then a 2@s cue-bid of their @s suit shows either   a limit  OR  a forcing   raise  in partner's Hearts.        Partner assumes the limit raise and either eccepts the invitation or not.
|n^|8|at|
If Opener declines the invitation, then responder can bid on if they have the "forcing" raise.
|n^|5|at|
^b  @.   MORE EXPENSIVE  cue-bid is  EITHER  an invitational raise in Opener's suit  OR,  more commonly, a strong forcing bid showing length and strength in the 4th (unbid) suit.
|n^|8|at|
So in that sequence just above, partner opens 1@h and their LHO bids 2@h showing @s and Diamonds.
Now 3@d from Responder shows EITHER a definitely invitational raise in @h OR, more commonly, a FORCING hand with CLUBS.
|n^|8|at|
So if you have the invitational hand with support for Partner, this is a STRONGER "invitation" than the merely limit raise (the cheaper cue-bid) again, partner assumes the invitational raise in their suit and you convert to Clubs if you have the forcing raise in Clubs.
|n^|5|at|
^b  @.   BID of the ^*b 4th suit ^*n  is merely competitive and direct suit raises of Opener's Suit are merely competitive
     or pre-emptive.  So
|n^|9|at|
1@h  -  (2@h[Michaels])  -  3@h/4@h   are merely COMPETITIVE or pre-emptive in Hearts    and 
1@h  -  (2@h[Michaels])  -  3@c          is  merely COMPETITIVE in Clubs.

^bSo when BOTH of Opps' suits are known, we have LOTS of options available.|
